[2] Ontario (multiple locations): poultry
Date: Mon 18 Apr 2022
Source: The London Free Press [edited]
https://lfpress.com/news/local-news/two-new-bird-flu-outbreaks-bring-ontario-total-to-16


Two new bird flu outbreaks bring Ontario total to 16
----------------------------------------------------
A new strain of bird flu has spread to 16 Ontario farms and 7 Canadian provinces, the Canadian Food Inspection Agency says. [The CFIA indicates this is not a new strain, but rather H5N1 with additional locations. - Mod.TG]

Another outbreak in the Township of South Glengarry, just west of the Quebec border, as well as 1 in the city of Markham north of Toronto were added to the federal agency's list during the long weekend.

Both outbreaks were confirmed last Thursday (14 Apr 2022).

The federal agency says outbreaks of the highly pathogenic H5N1 strain of avian flu have been found in poultry flocks in 7 provinces: Ontario, British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, Quebec, Nova Scotia and Newfoundland and Labrador.

The closest outbreaks to London are near Durham in the Municipality of West Grey (confirmed [9 Apr 2022]), Chatham-Kent (confirmed [6 Apr 2022]) and near Thamesford in western Oxford County (confirmed [28 Mar 2022]).

Control zones have been set up around each property, so officials can monitor movement of people and birds.

Craig Price, in charge of Ottawa's response to the outbreaks, wouldn't say how many birds have been destroyed at specific farms in order to protect the identities of the farmers involved.

Turkeys and ducks were infected in some of the initial outbreaks in Ontario, the federal agency says, and outbreaks have occurred at small farms and large operations.

The Canadian Food Inspection Agency is advising farmers to practise good biosecurity habits to safeguard flocks.

Bird flu is spread by wild birds, and is a significant concern as birds migrate to Canada, the agency has said.

The 1st Ontario outbreak in a poultry flock was confirmed in a turkey flock in Guelph/Eramosa Township on [27 Mar 2022].

In 2015, federal and provincial officials spent months containing and eventually eradicating another strain of bird flu. That outbreak was contained to 3 farms in Oxford County. About 80 000 birds, mostly turkeys, were wiped out.

[Byline: Dan Brown]

